  "prompt": "Why didn't the DSM-5 rename borderline personality disorder?",
  "response": "The DSM-5 (Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders, 5th edition) did not rename Borderline Personality Disorder (BPD) for several reasons:\n\n1. Historical recognition: The term \"borderline\" has been established in psychiatric literature for decades, and many professionals are familiar with it.\n\n2. Lack of consensus: There was no clear alternative name that gained widespread support among mental health professionals.\n\n3. Descriptive accuracy: While the term might seem outdated, it still carries some clinical meaning related to the disorder's original conceptualization.\n\n4. Continuity: Changing the name could cause confusion in research, clinical practice, and diagnostic communication.\n\nSome professionals have suggested alternative names like \"Emotional Dysregulation Disorder\" or \"Emotional Intensity Disorder,\" but these have not been officially adopted. The DSM-5 did make some modifications to the diagnostic criteria for BPD, but the name remained the same.\n\nThe disorder continues to be characterized by patterns of unstable interpersonal relationships, self-image, emotions, and significant impulsivity.",
